description.plain:
Hailing from Tupelo, Mississippi, Rae Sremmurd is a hip-hop duo comprised of brothers Swae Lee and Slim Jxmmi. Their name—which is “Ear Drummers” spelled backwards—is a reference to EarDrummers Entertainment, the label of producer Mike WiLL Made-It.

Rae Sremmurd rose to prominence in early 2014 with their breakout single “No Flex Zone,” which became a top 40 hit. Their follow-up “No Type” was even more successful, peaking at #16 on Billboard’s Hot 100. The group’s debut album SremmLife was released in January 2015.

The group’s second album SremmLife 2 was released in summer 2016. After initially struggling to recapture the success of their debut, the group’s single “Black Beatles” shot to #1 on the Hot 100 thanks to its placement in the viral “Mannequin Challenge” meme.

description.plain:
Swae Lee, Slim Jxmmi, Mike WiLL Made-It, and Gucci Mane team up on a track comparing themselves to the legendary English rock band The Beatles. The three rappers address their fame, women, and, most importantly, their money.

A month after its release as a Sremmlife 2 single “Black Beatles” gained popularity when it became affiliated with the “Mannequin Challenge,” a viral video sensation that captures people standing still as still as a mannequin while performing various acts. Sports teams, celebrities, schools, and even Rae Sremmurd themselves have participated in this challenge.
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cDLmej1aY-k
On November 14, 2016, it was revealed that the track had “rode the #MannequinChallenge” to the No. 1 spot on the Billboard Hot 100 chart. It was both Rae Sremmurd’s and Gucci Mane’s first No. 1 single on the Hot 100.

description.plain:
“Perplexing Pegasus” is a confident and braggadocious single that comes on the heels of Rae Sremmurd’s forthcoming work, SremmLife 3.

By Pegasus, Swae Lee and Slim Jxmmi are referring to a foreign car, so they ‘jump in’ and don’t hop on. The duo is widely known for their single “No Flex Zone” therefore it is “perplexing” that they are publiclly living so decadently. However, despite comparing the lyrics to Slim Jxmmi’s accident in Paris, this song was created before the 100K chain was lost in a crowd surf.

2 Chainz reveals via Instagram that he had a verse on this song that was removed at the last minute by producer Mike WiLL Made-It.

Swae told Zane Lowe about how this song came together:

In the song, Rae Sremmurd and The Weeknd talk about a conflicting relationship with a girl. They feel a mutual attraction, but are afraid of falling in love and the vulnerability that comes with it.

https://twitter.com/goSwaeLee/status/992195748522414080

Instead of sticking with just Beatles references, the group expands their reach to other areas of pop culture and music, making references to Axl Rose, Edge, Shawn Michaels, and more.

Since it’s release, this song has proven to be one of the album’s smash hits, with Swae Lee and Rae Sremmurd’s official Twitter accounts constantly retweeting people’s reactions to the song.

description.plain:
This is an unreleased remix of Rae Sremmurd’s “Swang”, featuring vocals from Quavo and Takeoff of Migos.

As well as the feature from Migos, the song features a much more laid-back instrumental, seemingly produced by Mike WiLL Made-It. It’s unknown why it never saw an official release.

The song was first teased by Music Mafia when they put the song up for auction. It leaked online on July 23, 2018.

description.plain:
“Look Alive” appears on Rae Sremmurd’s 2016 effort, SremmLife 2. This, however, is an early version of the song, at this point titled “Kill This Club”, that leaked online on February 7, 2019.

This version of the song is nearly identical to the final release, albeit more unfinished. Notably, Swae Lee’s verse is replaced with instrumental as it wasn’t recorded at the time, and the adlibs featured throughout are very different to the final release.

“Look Alive” appears on Rae Sremmurd’s 2016 effort, SremmLife 2. This, however, is an early version of the song, at this point titled “Kill This Club”, that leaked online on February 7, 2019.

This version of the song is nearly identical to the final release, albeit more unfinished. Notably, Swae Lee’s verse is replaced with instrumental as it wasn’t recorded at the time, and the adlibs featured throughout are very different to the final release.
